&nbsp;
Interesting. You have a rock that's been flying around for trillions of years or something, at a very high speed.. and yet, it's managed to maintain a perfectly pointy shape like that?
&nbsp;
Note also that the image displayed in the link is an artist's rendition. The actual footage of oumuamua is more like ... a dot. We're only making assumptions here..
&nbsp;
It's also relatively close to Earth right now.. albeit moving away. If it were really an interstellar spaceship, then the only way it could reach us would be through the deployment of smaller spacecraft. There's no way that a 800m long object moving at that speed could ever make a safe landing on our planet, it would be like landing the ISS. That would require a lot of fuel for deceleration alone.
&nbsp;
Should we be ready for an alien invasion? Actually, here's the catch: A civilization that is capable of interstellar travel, would also be capable of fully engineering their own minds and bodies. Such a civilization would be capable of erasing negative behavioral traits such as hostility, self-destructiveness, stupidity, greed, selfishness, etc. They would be like bees and ants.
&nbsp;
There would also be absolutely no need for them to invade Earth to steal its resources if they can perfectly colonize any random planet at their disposal out there in the universe, and mine any random asteroid for minerals, metals, gases, etc.
&nbsp;
If they ever did decide to waste their time trying to visit Earth, the only reason I could think of would be for the sheer glory of making contact with alien civilizations. We could practically save ourselves a dozen millennia of technological tinkering and get access to all the good stuff, so there's only something to be gained. 
&nbsp;
I suspect they might also consider us a danger to ourselves and maybe try to 'conquer' us for the sole purpose of correcting our behavior. After all, the biggest threat to Earth right now is nuclear warfare, not asteroids or gamma ray bursts or whatever.
&nbsp;
That said, let's not make conspiracy theories. If NASA were keeping secrets, they probably would have shut up about interstallar objects altogether. However, it's good to theorize - That's how we innovate and evolve, after all.

I think it probably goes without saying that a lot of us here in the dark corners of the internet have a problem socializing and meeting new people. I know I do..
&nbsp;
According to studies, the whole world seems to be slowly heading toward that direction as well ... as globalization, social media, and the demands of modern life seem to be eroding our humanity, weakening participation in the community and further dividing and alienating us all. It's no conspiracy.
&nbsp; 
So I thought to myself.. why don't we create a dating site based on machine learning and highly advanced artificial intelligence? A dating site that can find you a compatible soulmate, no matter what you look like, what perceived personality flaw you think you have, etc. Make it easy for the user, but also make the user work for it, and force them to explore and dig a little. Add a little mystery and treasure hunt, something lacking in a lot of dating sites these days.
&nbsp;
See, the biggest problem with dating sites these days is that .. they basically turn dating into a shopping game. You have a shelf full of products that you've never tried before .. ... and so the product with the prettiest label gets picked first.
&nbsp;
Also, people can be terrible at taking pictures. I've seen people who look amazing in real life, yet if you looked at their profile photos on Facebook, you'd probably run a hundred miles. There's a reason why the corporate world hires professional photographers.. there's a real art to it.. lens, lighting, focus, environment, what goes through your mind as you look into the camera, etc.
&nbsp;
A lot of these dating sites also claim that they're 'using scientifically-proven algorithms' .. but the fact remains that there's still a hell lot of lonely people out there who avoid dating sites like the plague, so it can't be true. Also, just because people have the same interests, doesn't mean they'll click. Sometimes opposites attract. Sometimes they don't.. 
&nbsp;
Dating sites also need to better understand and accommodate different sexual orientations in order to work.
&nbsp;
To sum it up, here's how the dating sites of the future might look like:
&nbsp;
**One:** Eliminate search engines and profile listings .. introduce 'virtual bars and clubs' where people get together and do stuff together, not necessarily with any intentions of dating straight away, either.
&nbsp;
This could almost be like an MMORPG, but none of that 'Second Life' horsecrap, either. Something that is grounded in reality. The graphics need to be outstanding. You also cannot modify your appearance in the game.. the character will be rendered to look exactly like yourself. If you're wearing pajama pants, you'll show up in the room wearing pajama pants.  
&nbsp;
Another way this could be accomplished is with 'webcam hangouts' .. although, for some reason sites like Omgele have died out as of recently, and I think it's because, frankly speaking.. it's kinda lame to talk to people when you can see them sitting in their bedrooms eating noodles. Maybe having a green-screen and/or a background swapping algorithm would help?
&nbsp;
**Two:** Introduce new matching algorithms based on real science. I'm surprised they haven't yet come up with a dating site that matches people based on facial similarities (EDIT: There used to be one in 2011, although it's died out https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Find_Your_FaceMate). Studies have actually shown that people who share similar facial features, are more likely to be attracted to each other. Apparently, beauty really is subjective, too .. and the 'prettiest people' out there just so happen to have the most 'common' facial features within a given population. A blend of averages.
&nbsp;
**Three:** Introduce artificial intelligence. You get teleported to 'virtual social clubs' where you can meet people who have been selected by this new experimental matching algorithm.
&nbsp;
**Four:** Create a virtual environment that leads to decreased social anxiety and inhibitions. Basically, it has to be the complete opposite of Facebook .. it has to be a place where Neuro-atypicals can feel like they're in paradise, but it can obviously accommodate Normies, and everybody else, too.
&nbsp;
**Five:** Privacy is also going to be an important issue, especially if we're going to involve the blockchain in this matter. Pictures won't be stored physically as img files.... rather, after you've uploaded your picture to the Javascript AI, the AI will create a unique identifier for you (let's call it.. your e-DNA). This unique identifier is then paired up with another unique identifier that shares similar facial features with you.. so instead of a database of users with pictures, you just have a database with raw public addresses. After you've been matched, both people are notified, but the conversation can only start if both participants agree to start a conversation / video chat.
&nbsp;
It could theoretically be possible to create software that renders a face based on this unique identifier, but it'll turn out rather cartoony, and won't be an exact image of the person, as it's only really used for matching purposes, not to fully identify somebody.

